- fnmatch-p-hang: tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst hangs the testee at 100%
  CPU; not yet isolated to a specific case within the file.

    ./shish tests/posix/fnmatch-p.tst

- fdtable-cycle-detection: the fdtable resolver has no real cycle
  detection, only a defensive depth cap; a genuinely cyclic
  redirection fails instead of resolving. Not yet isolated to a
  concrete repro; illustrative (unconfirmed) attempt:

    exec 3<&0
    exec 4<&3
    exec 3<&4

- sig-push-sigset-cast: sig_push() reinterprets sigset_t through an
  unsigned long*, UB on any ABI where sizeof(sigset_t) differs;
  currently harmless because the function is unused (dead code, not
  reachable from any shell script).

- sh-onsig-async-unsafe: sh_onsig(), the SIGCHLD handler, calls
  term_erase()/term_restore()/buffered i/o directly from signal-handler
  context; none of that is async-signal-safe. Any background job
  finishing exercises the handler, though the unsafety is a latent
  race, not a deterministic per-run failure.

    sleep 1 &
    sleep 2 &
    wait

- expand-glob-stack-overflow: found via an ASan build running
  tests/param.sh (which exercises heavy nested command-substitution +
  subshell use) -- a stack-buffer-overflow in
  src/expand/expand_glob.c:48. Not yet isolated to a minimal repro
  outside that test; noted here so it doesn't get lost, since the
  ASan run that found it was chasing an unrelated bug
  (fdstack-push-assertion, now fixed) that had been masking it.

    ./shish tests/param.sh   # under an ASan build


